<seg id=1> Schools In Zhejiang Disaster Area Resume Classes </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> XINHUA NEWS AGENCY WIRE Hangzhou, Sept. 2 (Shen Haixiong and Shen Xiquan reporting): Typhoon No. 17 has caused a lot of damage to the educational system in Zhejiang's disaster area. The number of schools with damaged buildings and facilities has reached one thousand and five hundred. </seg>
<seg id=3> Governments and citizens are actively working to recover from the disaster, and at present most elementary and junior high schools have resumed classes. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Zhejiang's education department recently sent work groups to Wenzhou, Taizhou and other school districts to assist in the work needed to resume classes. </seg>
<seg id=5> Twenty Wenzhou City education committee cadres were divided into seven groups and sent to Leqing, Ouhai, Dongtou, Pingyang and other areas to help with the preparation for resuming classes. Administration funds squeezed out for the recovery effort total 250 thousand yuan. </seg>
<seg id=6> Education administration departments from each city and county in the disaster area have offered to lower tuition fees or to give help to parents' who have experienced hardship due to the disaster, and have promised that students will be able to begin classes on time. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> School leaders and educational workers in the affected areas have volunteered to go to school early, cleaning up the school grounds, carrying out disinfection procedures, and helping to repair damaged buildings. </seg>
<seg id=8> The Wenzhou City Education Committee and the city's Communist Youth League have linked up with teachers and students from the disaster areas to carry out a fund-raising campaign they've called "Love for Schools in the Disaster Area". The city has received more than one million yuan from various donations so far. </seg>
</p>
